Trump has stressed Hamas must disarm, but the Palestinian group has linked giving up its weapons to the establishment of a Palestinian state.

In Madagascar, a severe education crisis is trapped in a cycle of deep poverty. 
UN data shows over a million children are out of school, with only a third completing high school.
The national university enrolment rate is just 6%. 
Schools are chronically overcrowded and under-resourced, with nearly all 10-year-olds unable to read a simple text.
This widespread lack of opportunity recently fuelled youth-led anti-government protests, which contributed to a military coup. 
The situation ensures the crisis will impact generations to come.

Al Jazeera’s Fahmida Miller reports from the capital Antananarivo.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
France’s former president Nicolas Sarkozy has arrived at a prison in Paris to start serving a five-year jail sentence.
The 70-year-old leader arrived at La Sante prison in a police car on Tuesday morning, becoming the first former head of an European Union state to be jailed.
Sarkozy was sentenced to five years after being found guilty last month of criminal conspiracy, due to having accepted millions of euros in illegal payments from the late Libyan ruler, Muammar Gaddafi, to fund his 2007 election campaign.
He has always denied the charges. His lawyers said as he arrived to start his sentence that a request for release had been immediately filed.
“It is not a former president of the republic being jailed this morning, but an innocent man,” he said on X on his way to prison. “Truth will prevail.”
Dozens of supporters and family members had stood outside Sarkozy’s home from early Tuesday, some holding up framed portraits.

Al Jazeera’s Jonah Hull reports.

description:
US Vice President JD Vance visited Israel alongside Middle East envoy Steve Witkoff and adviser Jared Kushner to assess progress on the Gaza ceasefire. Vance said the truce implementation was “going very well” but stressed that reconstruction and security must come first before deciding Gaza’s long-term governance. Witkoff described the US-led ceasefire coordination centre in Israel as a model for future peace efforts. Kushner said progress was being made on retrieving Israeli captives’ remains and praised coordination with the UN on aid delivery. Vance ruled out any US troops in Gaza and said Hamas must disarm, adding that lasting peace would take time and patience.

Following the press conference, our reporter in Amman, Nour Odeh, said Palestinians were omitted and their suffering under rubble went unrecognised.
The focus remained overwhelmingly on Israel, including security, captives, and objections to international participation in Gaza stabilisation.
Messages from the conference

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Sanae Takaichi has become Japan's first female prime minister. 
Japan's parliament has voted in the ultraconservative hardliner, after her party signed a last-minute coalition deal with another right-wing party.
Takaichi replaces Shigeru Ishiba, who resigned after his coalition lost parliamentary elections in July.
It's seen as a shift to the right, in a country worried about rising prices, a sluggish economy and immigration.
 
Stephen Nagy is a Visiting Fellow at the Japan Institute of International Affairs.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
This medical evacuation has been organised by the World Health Organization.

We know that these 50 Palestinians are either patients whose condition is deteriorating due to disease or who were wounded by Israeli forces and require urgent medical treatment.

What is not clear yet is the process. We do not know whether they are going to be evacuated from hospitals. We don’t know if the Rafah crossing is going to be used or Karem Abu Salem. The Rafah crossing should have been opened since last Wednesday under the ceasefire agreement.

A lot of Palestinians are waiting to leave Gaza, either for medical treatment or to reunite with family members they were separated from during the war.

Al Jazeera’s Hind Khoudary has more from Deir el-Balah in central Gaza, Palestine.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Bolivia's president-elect Rodrigo Paz has promised to restore diplomatic ties with Washington, following years of frosty relations under his left-wing predecessors.
After winning Sunday's run-off vote, he's set to become the country's first conservative leader in nearly 20 years when he takes office next month, but he is facing huge challenges.

Al Jazeera’s Alessandro Rampietti reports from La Paz, Bolivia.
